body:
We're using Lombok annotations, which replace `Object.equals()` with custom implementation of `equals()`. Pay attention to the annotation `@EqualsAndHashCode(of = "label")` of `Label.Smart`. More about Lombok: http://projectlombok.org/features/EqualsAndHashCode.html

So, I think, it's not a bug, and we're compliant with `(x.compareTo(y)==0) == (x.equals(y))`. @pbao what do you think?

Nevertheless, I think it's worth to introduce a unit test for all our classes that implement `compareTo()` and confirm that they follow the convention of JDK. So, this is a good report, but it should be renamed and changed a bit (if you agree with what I said above). The problem should be described as "`compareTo()` methods are not tested".

OK I can see the EqualsAndHashCode annotation on Label.Smart but I don't understand why that would generate an equals method on the anonymous inner class defined on line 341 com.jcabi.github.Issue since that is a sibling of Label.Smart not a subclass (or rather it just happens to implement the same interface).
Ah, I see, you're right, that class is not processed by lombok. This is definitely a bug, thanks for reporting it
